05782nam a22008655i 9780814772959DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147729597 a10.18574/nyu/9780814772959.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548663  a(OCoLC)782878056  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS135.E89 M9 2006 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a304.87304700aMy Future Is in America :bAutobiographies of Eastern European Jewish Immigrants /ced. by Daniel Soyer, Jocelyn Cohen. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Annotations and Transliteration -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Success or Failure? -- tChapter 2. Why I Came to America -- tChapter 3. I Have Nothing to Complain About -- tChapter 4. Why I Left My Old Home and What I Have Accomplished in America -- tChapter 5. What Drove Me to America and My Experiences in Europe and America -- tChapter 6. My Future Is in America -- tChapter 7. The Movies Pale in Comparison -- tChapter 8. Why I Left the Old Country and What I Have Accomplished in America -- tChapter 9. I Haven’t Lost Anything by Coming to America -- tGlossary -- tIndex -- tAbout the Editors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1942, YIVO held a contest for the best autobiography by a Jewish immigrant on the theme “Why I Left the Old Country and What I Have Accomplished in America.” Chosen from over two hundred entries, and translated from Yiddish, the nine life stories in My Future Is in America provide a compelling portrait of American Jewish life in the immigrant generation at the turn of the twentieth century.The writers arrived in America in every decade from the 1890s to the 1920s. They include manual workers, shopkeepers, housewives, communal activists, and professionals who came from all parts of Eastern Europe and ushered in a new era in American Jewish history. In their own words, the immigrant writers convey the complexities of the transition between the Old and New Worlds.An Introduction places the writings in historical and literary context, and annotations explain historical and cultural allusions made by the writers. This unique volume introduces readers to the complex world of Yiddish-speaking immigrants while at the same time elucidating important themes and topics of interest to those in immigration studies, ethnic studies, labor history, and literary studies.Published in conjunction with the YIVO Institute for Jewish Research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aImmigrantsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aJewsxBiographyxEurope, Eastern. 0aJewszEurope, EasternvBiography. 0aJews, East EuropeanxBiographyxUnited States. 0aJews, East EuropeanzUnited StatesvBiography. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh1 aCohen, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jocelyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDomnitz, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Bertha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Minnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrone, Shmuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKusnetz, Chaim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKusnetz, Minnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReisman, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchoenfeld, Rose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc